<font color="#FF0000">ON PERSONAL ACCOUNTABILITY...</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 19 20:16:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz made a point that surely strikes home when calling<br>
for the specifics of who actually did the deeds while hiding<br>
behind the all-obscuring curtain of &quot;government.&quot; This would<br>
go a very long way to provide some compelling motivation to <br>
do the right thing.  Nothing like accountability to sharpen<br>
a person's moral senses.<br><br>
On a slightly different tack, I am glad that Doc has come to<br>
reexamine his beliefs and come to some conclusions based <br>
upon some light and soul-searching.  A good thing for <br>
anybody to do.  But I'm here to say to all that personal<br>
growth for one person is a small matter in the larger <br>
scheme of things.  There are still people who cling to a <br>
blindly biased set of preconceptions of VN vets and who will <br>
act upon them without regard to the moral implications of <br>
their acts, then hide behind an all-obscuring curtain <br>
whenever available.  <br><br>
As with the medical personnel who perpetrated the Tuskegee<br>
studies, these unchanged and unaccountable persons continue<br>
to do today much as they had when they anonymously called <br>
the families of KIAs to gloat or harrassed those who <br>
survived.  These folks are in government and the business <br>
world, hiding and acting upon their biases.  Along with many<br>
VN vets, I have run nose-first into this over many years <br>
(but decline to post these circumstances here).<br><br>
For me it is as if the war still rages, with these self-<br>
declared enemies hiding, sniping and planting mines.  It <br>
would be wonderful to at last have a truce, but it seems <br>
unlikely.  It is an enraging set of circumstances caused by<br>
the lack of moral courage of these gutless individuals.<br><br>
Anyway, good for you Doc Spatz.  One down, a whole pile to <br>
go (only God knows how many).<br><br>
TJ, 5th SFGA, MACSOG(CCN) 69-71
